  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On Buddhism's Confusion Regarding the Distinction Between Principle and Vessel
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Principle is reason itself—that which transcends form. Vessel is matter—that which is bound by form. The great source of principle flows from Heaven and pervades all things, present at every moment and in every circumstance. Within the heart-mind and body dwells the principle of the heart-mind and body. Near at hand, it manifests in the relations between father and son, ruler and subject, husband and wife, elder and younger, friend and friend. Extending far, it reaches heaven, earth, and all creatures—each possessing its own principle. Humans cannot exist between heaven and earth for a single day apart from things, standing alone. Therefore, in all my dealings with affairs and engagement with things, I must exhaust the principle of each, without the slightest deviation. This is why our Confucian learning allows each—from the heart to the body, from self to others to things—to fulfill its nature completely, leaving nothing impenetrable.

    Principle, though not mixed with vessel, cannot be separated from it. The Buddhists, though gaining nothing true of principle through their understanding, have labored long in their contemplation and possess something that seems like glimpses of truth. Yet it is as one peering at heaven through a hollow reed—looking only upward, unable to reach in all directions. What they see inevitably falls into one-sidedness.

    Seeing that principle does not mingle with vessel, they split the two asunder, declaring: "All that bears form is illusion. Only by seeing forms as no-form do we perceive the Tathagata." Thus they desperately seek to escape the realm of multiplicity and fall into emptiness and silence.

    Seeing that principle cannot be separated from vessel, they mistake vessel for principle, saying: "Both good and evil are mind alone. All phenomena are consciousness. Follow all things; act without acting." Thus they become reckless and unrestrained, leaving nothing undone—what the Master Cheng called the blocked who become withered, the rough who become licentious.

    Yet what they call principle, pointing to the mind, actually falls into that which is bound by form, while they remain unaware. How lamentable!
  footnotes:
    - 道 (Principle) and 器 (Vessel) are key Neo-Confucian concepts from the Book of Changes. This text critiques Buddhist philosophy through the lens of this crucial distinction.
    - 管窺 ('peering through a hollow reed') is a classical metaphor for limited and biased perspective.
    - The reference to 程子 (Master Cheng) alludes to Neo-Confucian philosophical teachings on the dangers of imbalanced spiritual cultivation.
    - 形而上/形而下 (transcending form/bound by form) derives from Daoist and Neo-Confucian metaphysics.
